  "body": "I found that kubelet will not allocate hostports specified from initContainers.\r\nAnd PodFitsHostPorts in kube-scheduler does not take initContainer into consideration.\r\n\r\nAlso, kube-apiserver think such pod is illegal, but I think it OK.\r\n```\r\n$ cat two-files-counter-pod-streaming-sidecar.yaml \r\napiVersion: v1\r\nkind: Pod\r\nmetadata:\r\n  name: counter\r\nspec:\r\n  hostname: name\r\n  subdomain: subdomain\r\n  initContainers:\r\n  - name: init-step1\r\n    image: busybox\r\n    args:\r\n    - /bin/sh\r\n    - -c\r\n    - >\r\n      sleep 10;\r\n    ports:\r\n      - containerPort: 8081\r\n        hostPort: 8081\r\n  - name: init-step2\r\n    image: busybox\r\n    args:\r\n    - /bin/sh\r\n    - -c\r\n    - >\r\n      sleep 10;\r\n    ports:\r\n      - containerPort: 8081\r\n        hostPort: 8081    # this port does not conflict with the previous one, because initContainer runs in sequential order.\r\n  containers:\r\n  containers:\r\n  - name: count\r\n    image: busybox\r\n    args:\r\n    - /bin/sh\r\n    - -c\r\n    - >\r\n      i=0;\r\n      while true;\r\n      do\r\n        i=$((i+1));\r\n        sleep $i;\r\n      done\r\n$ kubectl create -f two-files-counter-pod-streaming-sidecar.yaml \r\nThe Pod \"counter\" is invalid: spec.initContainers[1].ports[0].hostPort: Duplicate value: \"TCP//8081\"\r\n```\r\n\r\nWe should make the behavior of spec.HostPorts in initContainer clear",
